  "prompt": "Why is white colour only showing once in the spectrum?",
  "response": "In the visible light spectrum (rainbow colors), white is not actually a spectral color like red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, and violet. White is not a single wavelength of light, but rather a combination of all wavelengths of visible light together.\n\nHere's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Spectral colors are pure, monochromatic wavelengths of light\n- Each color in the rainbow represents a specific wavelength\n- These colors range from roughly 380-700 nanometers\n\n2. White is not a spectral color\n- It is the result of all visible wavelengths being present simultaneously\n- When all colors of the spectrum are mixed together, our eyes perceive white\n\n3. How white is perceived\n- When light contains equal amounts of all visible wavelengths\n- When light reflects off a surface that reflects all wavelengths equally\n- In a prism or rainbow, white is not shown as a distinct color because it is a combination, not a single wavelength\n\n4. Color perception\n- Our eyes have three types of cone cells sensitive to different wavelengths\n- When all these cones are stimulated equally, we perceive white\n\nSo white appears only once (or not at all) in the spectrum because it's not a single color, but a combination of all colors.",
